0:{"buildId":"hCurFP6vqgVtfXUmC_lIR","rsc":["$","$1","c",{"children":[["$","article",null,{"className":"bg-white","children":[["$","div",null,{"className":"max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8 pt-6","children":["$","nav",null,{"className":"flex items-center space-x-2 text-sm text-gray-600","children":[["$","$L2",null,{"href":"/","className":"hover:text-blue-600","children":"Home"}],[["$","div","/car-seats",{"className":"flex items-center space-x-2","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"text-gray-400","children":"/"}],["$","$L2",null,{"href":"/car-seats","className":"hover:text-blue-600","children":"Car Seats"}]]}],["$","div","/car-seats/car-seat-installation-mistakes",{"className":"flex items-center space-x-2","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"text-gray-400","children":"/"}],["$","span",null,{"className":"text-gray-900 font-medium","children":"Car Seat Installation Mistakes: Common Errors That Compromise Safety"}]]}]]]}]}],["$","section",null,{"className":"max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8 py-12 border-b border-gray-200","children":[["$","h1",null,{"className":"text-4xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4","children":"Car Seat Installation Mistakes: Common Errors That Compromise Safety"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-lg text-gray-600","children":"Identify and fix common car seat installation errors. Learn what mistakes 70% of parents make and how to install correctly for maximum safety."}]]}],["$","section",null,{"className":"max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8 py-12","children":["$","div",null,{"className":"prose prose-lg max-w-none text-gray-700","children":[["$","h2","0",{"className":"text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4","children":"Introduction"}],["$","p","1",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"Car seat safety depends not just on buying the right seat, but installing it correctly. Yet studies show approximately 70-80% of car seats are installed with at least one significant error. Some mistakes are minor; others dramatically reduce crash protection. This guide identifies the most common installation errors, explains why they matter, and provides step-by-step correction."}],["$","h2","2",{"className":"text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4","children":"Why Installation Matters"}],["$","p","3",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"A correctly installed car seat can reduce injury risk by 71% in frontal crashes and 67% in side-impact crashes. An incorrectly installed seat loses this protection dramatically. The difference between right and wrong installation can mean the difference between minor injuries and severe trauma."}],["$","h2","4",{"className":"text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4","children":"The Top 10 Installation Mistakes"}],["$","h2","5",{"className":"text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4","children":"#Mistake #1: Incorrect Seatbelt Path"}],["$","p","6",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**The Error**: The seatbelt (or LATCH connector) doesn't thread through the correct path on the car seat frame."}],["$","p","7",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**Why it matters**: If the belt isn't routed correctly, the seat won't stay firmly anchored during a crash. The seat tilts, slides, or rotates—reducing restraint effectiveness."}],["$","p","8",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**How to fix it**:\n1. Consult your car seat manual for the exact belt path (differs by brand/model)\n2. Find the belt guide on the car seat (usually red or colored webbing channels)\n3. Thread the seatbelt or LATCH straps through the correct guides, following the manual precisely\n4. After routing, pull the seatbelt tight and lock it\n5. Test: Grasp the car seat where it connects to the seatbelt. You shouldn't be able to move it more than 1 inch forward or side-to-side"}],"$L3","$L4","$L5","$L6","$L7","$L8","$L9","$La","$Lb","$Lc","$Ld","$Le","$Lf","$L10","$L11","$L12","$L13","$L14","$L15","$L16","$L17","$L18","$L19","$L1a","$L1b","$L1c","$L1d","$L1e","$L1f","$L20","$L21","$L22","$L23","$L24","$L25","$L26","$L27","$L28","$L29","$L2a","$L2b","$L2c","$L2d","$L2e","$L2f","$L30","$L31","$L32","$L33","$L34","$L35","$L36","$L37","$L38","$L39","$L3a","$L3b","$L3c","$L3d","$L3e","$L3f","$L40","$L41","$L42","$L43","$L44","$L45","$L46","$L47","$L48","$L49","$L4a","$L4b","$L4c","$L4d","$L4e","$L4f","$L50"]}]}],"$L51","$L52"]}],["$L53"],"$L54"]}],"loading":null,"isPartial":false}
3:["$","p","9",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**Pro tip**: Many car seats have the belt path printed on the side or bottom. Use it as a reference while installing."}]
4:["$","h2","10",{"className":"text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4","children":"#Mistake #2: LATCH Strap Not Tight Enough"}]
5:["$","p","11",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**The Error**: The LATCH (Lower Anchors and Tethering for Children) straps are connected to the anchors but aren't pulled tight enough."}]
6:["$","p","12",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**Why it matters**: A loose LATCH connection allows the seat to move 2+ inches during a crash. Loose = reduced protection."}]
7:["$","p","13",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**How to fix it**:\n1. Thread LATCH straps through the correct path on your car seat\n2. Connect both straps to the LATCH anchors under your vehicle's seats (usually two metal hooks under the seat cushion)\n3. Pull the straps tight—this requires effort. You should feel significant resistance.\n4. Tighten until you can only move the seat 1 inch or less when you grasp it firmly\n5. Many LATCH straps have \"tightness indicators\" (belts that change color or texture when taut)"}]
8:["$","p","14",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**Reality**: Most parents under-tighten LATCH straps because they worry about over-tightening. Modern LATCH systems are designed to withstand significant force. Err on the side of tighter."}]
9:["$","h2","15",{"className":"text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4","children":"#Mistake #3: Using Both LATCH and Seatbelt (Over-Anchoring)"}]
a:["$","p","16",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**The Error**: Installing the car seat with both LATCH AND the seatbelt at the same time."}]
b:["$","p","17",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**Why it matters**: Some assume redundancy is safer. It's not. Over-anchoring can cause the seat to shift or tilt unevenly during a crash. Use one or the other, not both."}]
c:["$","p","18",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**How to fix it**:\n1. Choose one installation method: either LATCH or seatbelt (not both)\n2. If using LATCH: Connect both lower anchors. Do NOT also use the seatbelt\n3. If using seatbelt: Thread the seatbelt through the belt path. Do NOT also use LATCH\n4. If your vehicle doesn't have LATCH, seatbelt installation is fine (older vehicles, certain seat positions)"}]
d:["$","p","19",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**Note**: The tether strap (if present) is used regardless of whether you use LATCH or seatbelt. The tether provides additional stability and is always recommended."}]
e:["$","h2","20",{"className":"text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4","children":"#Mistake #4: Wrong Seat Position"}]
f:["$","p","21",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**The Error**: Installing the car seat in the wrong vehicle seat location (middle, wrong side, front passenger seat)."}]
10:["$","p","22",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**Why it matters**: Different seat locations provide different levels of crash protection. The safest position is rear center (behind the driver or passenger). Side positions are slightly less safe. Front passenger seats are unsuitable for most car seats (air bag hazard)."}]
11:["$","p","23",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**Correct positions** (in order of preference):\n1. **Rear center** — Safest position; equidistant from side-impact zones\n2. **Rear driver-side** — Safe; slightly higher risk in side-impact on that side\n3. **Rear passenger-side** — Safe; slightly higher risk in side-impact on that side\n4. **Front passenger seat** — Only acceptable for convertible seats in booster mode if no rear seats available AND air bag is disabled (very rare scenario)"}]
12:["$","p","24",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**How to fix it**: Install your car seat in the rear center position if possible. If your vehicle doesn't have a rear center seat (some coupes), use either rear side position."}]
13:["$","h2","25",{"className":"text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4","children":"#Mistake #5: Improper Recline Angle"}]
14:["$","p","26",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**The Error**: The car seat reclines too far forward or sits too upright."}]
15:["$","p","27",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**Why it matters**: Infant car seats must recline at a specific angle (usually 30-45 degrees) to protect the baby's head, neck, and spine. Too upright causes baby's head to flop forward. Too reclined can obstruct airflow."}]
16:["$","p","28",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**How to fix it**:\n1. Consult your car seat manual for the correct recline angle (usually 30-45 degrees)\n2. Most car seats have a recline indicator (a level or angle markings on the side)\n3. Adjust the seat's recline foot or base until the indicator shows the correct angle\n4. Many car seats also provide a vehicle-specific tilt guide—use it to ensure the vehicle's own tilt (some vehicles naturally tilt back slightly) doesn't throw off the seat angle\n5. Test: Place a small level on the seat. It should show approximately 30-45 degrees."}]
17:["$","p","29",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**Reality**: This mistake is surprisingly common because parents don't realize recline angle matters. Correct recline prevents positional asphyxia (baby's chin dropping to chest) and ensures proper crash protection."}]
18:["$","h2","30",{"className":"text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4","children":"#Mistake #6: Harness Straps Too Loose"}]
19:["$","p","31",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**The Error**: The harness straps (which hold your baby in the seat) are loose or don't snugly secure your baby."}]
1a:["$","p","32",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**Why it matters**: A loose harness allows your baby to move around inside the seat. During a crash, movement = injury risk."}]
1b:["$","p","33",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**How to fix it**:\n1. Place your baby in the seat fully dressed (test with winter coat if you use one)\n2. Tighten the harness straps at the shoulders and crotch until they're snug (you shouldn't be able to pinch excess webbing)\n3. Place one finger under each strap to verify tightness (snug, but not causing discomfort)\n4. The straps should be at or slightly above your baby's shoulders in rear-facing mode\n5. Re-tighten after every use (straps loosen naturally as baby wiggles during the drive)"}]
1c:["$","p","34",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**Pro tip**: Tighten harness before every trip, not just during initial installation. Most parents get this right but fail to re-tighten regularly."}]
1d:["$","h2","35",{"className":"text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4","children":"#Mistake #7: Harness Height Wrong for Rear-Facing"}]
1e:["$","p","36",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**The Error**: Harness slots are placed below your baby's shoulders (too low) or above the head (too high) in rear-facing mode."}]
1f:["$","p","37",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**Why it matters**: Harness height ensures the restraint forces during a crash are absorbed by the baby's chest and shoulders—not the neck or head."}]
20:["$","p","38",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**Correct positioning** (rear-facing):\n- Harness slots should be AT or slightly BELOW baby's shoulders\n- If baby is too large and shoulders are above top harness slot, it's time to transition to forward-facing (consult your seat's weight/height limits first)"}]
21:["$","p","39",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**How to fix it**:\n1. Assess your baby's shoulder position relative to harness slots\n2. If shoulders are below slots, you need a higher slot—look for a mechanism to raise the slots (some seats have a tool, others involve repositioning webbing)\n3. If shoulders are above all available slots, your baby may be too large for the infant seat. Consult the manual's weight/height limits and potentially transition to a convertible seat"}]
22:["$","p","40",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**Note**: You can't just move to a higher slot without following the manual's instructions. Improper slot adjustment creates misalignment in crash protection."}]
23:["$","h2","41",{"className":"text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4","children":"#Mistake #8: Not Using the Tether Strap (Forward-Facing)"}]
24:["$","p","42",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**The Error**: The tether strap (an additional upper strap that anchors to the vehicle's tether anchor) is not connected."}]
25:["$","p","43",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**Why it matters**: The tether strap provides crucial upper-body restraint in forward-facing mode. It prevents excessive forward motion during a frontal crash. Without it, your child's head and upper body move too far forward."}]
26:["$","p","44",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**How to fix it**:\n1. Locate the tether strap on your car seat (upper attachment point)\n2. Locate the tether anchor in your vehicle (usually on the back of the seat, the floor, or the roof—consult your vehicle manual)\n3. Attach the tether strap to the anchor\n4. Tighten until snug (you should feel resistance)\n5. Test: You should not be able to pull the seat forward more than 1 inch"}]
27:["$","p","45",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**Reality**: Many parents don't even know the tether strap exists or think it's optional. It's not optional; it's essential for forward-facing protection."}]
28:["$","h2","46",{"className":"text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4","children":"#Mistake #9: Wrong Installation for Your Vehicle Make/Model"}]
29:["$","p","47",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**The Error**: Installing the car seat without consulting your vehicle-specific installation guide."}]
2a:["$","p","48",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**Why it matters**: Different vehicles have different LATCH anchor locations, seatbelt paths, and compatibility quirks. What works for a Honda might not work for a Ford. A car seat installed incorrectly for your vehicle might not provide adequate protection."}]
2b:["$","p","49",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**How to fix it**:\n1. Get your car's owner's manual (physical copy or PDF from manufacturer's website)\n2. Find the car seat installation section\n3. Also consult your car seat manual, which often includes vehicle-specific guidelines\n4. Many car seat brands publish vehicle-specific installation guides on their websites\n5. If instructions conflict, contact the car seat manufacturer—they can clarify compatibility"}]
2c:["$","p","50",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**Pro tip**: Some car seats work better in certain vehicle seat positions due to seat shape. Your vehicle's back seat might naturally tilt in a way that works well (or poorly) with your seat's design. Testing different positions (driver side, passenger side, middle) can reveal the best fit."}]
2d:["$","h2","51",{"className":"text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4","children":"#Mistake #10: Forgetting to Transition (Rear-Facing to Forward-Facing or to Booster)"}]
2e:["$","p","52",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**The Error**: Keeping your child in a car seat past the appropriate transition point (either age, height, or weight limit)."}]
2f:["$","p","53",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**Why it matters**: Overweight or overheight children in seats designed for smaller children don't receive proper protection. The harness doesn't fit correctly, the seat's design assumes different proportions, and your child's safety is compromised."}]
30:["$","p","54",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**How to fix it**:\n1. Consult your car seat manual for height and weight limits (usually printed on the seat or in the manual)\n2. Measure and weigh your child regularly\n3. Track the limits—when your child reaches the limit, transition to the next stage\n4. Don't wait for your child to outgrow the seat significantly. Transition when they reach the manufacturer's specified limit"}]
31:["$","p","55",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**Reality**: Many parents delay transitions because they're emotionally ready (their child \"looks\" like they still fit) or they don't want to buy new seats. Safety requires timely transitions. Buy a convertible seat that serves multiple stages if budget is a concern."}]
32:["$","h2","56",{"className":"text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4","children":"Common Installation Myths Debunked"}]
33:["$","p","57",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**Myth**: \"The middle seat is too hard to reach; the side seats are fine.\""}]
34:["$","p","58",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**Truth**: The rear middle seat is safest. Yes, it's harder to install and access. This is worth the extra effort for maximum protection."}]
35:["$","p","59",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**Myth**: \"I can over-tighten LATCH straps and break them.\""}]
36:["$","p","60",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**Truth**: LATCH straps are engineered for crash forces much greater than you can apply by hand. Tight is good. Over-tightening by hand isn't possible."}]
37:["$","p","61",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**Myth**: \"My car's seatbelt has a lock feature, so I don't need LATCH.\""}]
38:["$","p","62",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**Truth**: Some vehicles have seatbelt locking mechanisms that make seatbelt installation as effective as LATCH. Check your vehicle manual. If seatbelt locking is available, you can use either method. LATCH is often simpler."}]
39:["$","p","63",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**Myth**: \"I installed it once; I don't need to check it again.\""}]
3a:["$","p","64",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**Truth**: Check installation before every trip (especially after long breaks). Straps loosen. Tether attachments can slip. A quick check takes 30 seconds and prevents disasters."}]
3b:["$","p","65",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**Myth**: \"Preemie inserts and body positioners are essential.\""}]
3c:["$","p","66",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**Truth**: Some manufacturers include inserts to provide proper positioning for small or preemature babies. Others are unnecessary. Check if your seat includes the insert and use it if provided. Don't buy aftermarket inserts without verifying they don't interfere with harness positioning."}]
3d:["$","h2","67",{"className":"text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4","children":"Installation Resources and Help"}]
3e:["$","p","68",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**If you're unsure about your installation:**"}]
3f:["$","p","69",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"1. **Consult both manuals**: Your car seat manual and your vehicle owner's manual\n2. **Visit a certified car seat inspection station**: Many hospitals, fire departments, and car seat retailers offer free inspections. They'll verify your installation and correct any errors\n3. **Use manufacturer online resources**: Most car seat brands have YouTube videos demonstrating installation\n4. **Call the car seat manufacturer**: If you're confused, call them. They'll walk you through installation"}]
40:["$","p","70",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"**Finding a certified inspector**: Visit the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration (NHTSA) website or search \"car seat inspection near me.\" Many locations offer free appointments."}]
41:["$","h2","71",{"className":"text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4","children":"The Installation Check: Step-by-Step"}]
42:["$","p","72",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"Before assuming your installation is correct, perform this check:"}]
43:["$","p","73",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"1. **Grasp the seat firmly** where it connects to the seatbelt or LATCH (typically the bottom of the seat)\n2. **Attempt to move it** side-to-side and front-to-back with moderate force\n3. **Acceptable movement**: Less than 1 inch in any direction\n4. **If movement exceeds 1 inch**: Tighten the seatbelt or LATCH straps and re-test\n5. **Re-test before each drive** (straps loosen over time)"}]
44:["$","p","74",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"A properly installed seat is remarkably solid and resistant to movement. If you can move it easily, tighten."}]
45:["$","h2","75",{"className":"text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4","children":"Transition Checklist: When to Move to Next Stage"}]
46:["$","h2","76",{"className":"text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4","children":"#Rear-Facing to Forward-Facing"}]
47:["$","p","77",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"Your child is ready to transition when they meet ALL of these criteria:\n- [ ] Age 2 or older\n- [ ] Weight within the forward-facing limit (usually 40-50 lbs max for infant seats, 40-65 lbs for convertibles)\n- [ ] Height allows shoulders to be AT or below the top harness slot in forward-facing position\n- [ ] Developmentally ready (can follow safety instructions and sit calmly)"}]
48:["$","h2","78",{"className":"text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4","children":"#Forward-Facing to Booster"}]
49:["$","p","79",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"Your child is ready to transition when they meet ALL of these criteria:\n- [ ] Age 5 or older (many experts recommend 6+)\n- [ ] Weight within the forward-facing limit (usually 40-80 lbs depending on seat)\n- [ ] Height at least 44-48 inches (varies by booster)\n- [ ] Shoulders above the top harness slot (no more room for growth in harnessed mode)\n- [ ] Can sit still and follow safety rules"}]
4a:["$","h2","80",{"className":"text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4","children":"#Booster to Vehicle Seatbelt Only"}]
4b:["$","p","81",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"Your child is ready to transition when they meet ALL of these criteria:\n- [ ] Age 8 or older (legal minimum in most states)\n- [ ] Height at least 57-60 inches (typically 4'8\" to 5')\n- [ ] Weight at least 80 lbs\n- [ ] Can sit upright in the vehicle seat without slouching for entire trips\n- [ ] Vehicle's seatbelt fits properly (belt crosses chest at shoulder, lap belt across hip)"}]
4c:["$","p","82",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"Test seatbelt fit: Have your child sit normally. The lap belt should cross the hip/upper thigh (not the stomach). The shoulder belt should cross the shoulder/chest (not the neck). If either is misaligned, continue using a booster."}]
4d:["$","h2","83",{"className":"text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4","children":"Conclusion"}]
4e:["$","p","84",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"Car seat installation errors are common but correctable. The 10 mistakes outlined above account for the vast majority of incorrect installations. Tighten LATCH or seatbelt firmly, position the seat correctly, ensure proper recline, keep the harness snug, and use the tether strap."}]
4f:["$","p","85",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"Before you assume your installation is correct, test it. Grasp the seat and verify movement is minimal. Check the angle. Verify the harness is snug. If you're unsure, don't guess—contact a certified inspector or the car seat manufacturer. A few minutes of installation verification can mean the difference between a child walking away from a crash and serious injury."}]
50:["$","p","86",{"className":"text-gray-700 leading-relaxed my-4","children":"Most importantly: Correct installation today protects your child in tomorrow's crash. This is worth your attention."}]
51:["$","$L55",null,{"pagePath":"/car-seats/car-seat-installation-mistakes","siteName":"thefamilypick"}]
52:["$","section",null,{"className":"max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8 py-8 border-t border-gray-200","children":["$","$L2",null,{"href":"/car-seats","className":"inline-block bg-blue-600 text-white px-6 py-2 rounded font-semibold hover:bg-blue-700","children":"Back to Car Seats Comparison"}]}]
53:["$","script","script-0",{"src":"/_next/static/chunks/5935fefdd9fc8f83.js","async":true}]
54:["$","$L56",null,{"children":["$","$57",null,{"name":"Next.MetadataOutlet","children":"$@58"}]}]
58:null
